text:
Inside is a pretty cool game. It has a very interesting setting, mysterious plot and a lot of philosophical themes to keep you thinking.
Many thanks to Gura for playing this! If she likes this, she should consider playing Limbo, which is a similar game made by the same creators. Though I prefer Inside more.

Alternatively she might want to consider playing Little Nightmares 1 and 2. It is also a puzzle platformer with an interesting setting and vague enough storyline for players to interpret it however they wish. Though the puzzles are less about getting from A to Be and more about how to evade enemies.

For example, if you talk about Jack Black you will later get ads about movies like School of Rock and..." Either this helpful page also reads my phone or I just near impossible odds here.

Or maybe phones very specifically love Jack Black.

text: Respectfully, this is not a racist remark. In my region, there are many figures of speech related to food items. "I'll make mince meat out of you!", "You were cooked!", "Oh man, thanks for the save, I was about to become chop suey back there!", or in Gura's case "If I had a..." (weapon?) "... We'd be having chop suey for lunch". It's a similar figure of speech to the first example "I'll make mince meat out of you!", meaning if in the game she had a weapon, she'd make chop suey out of the dog, or in simpler terms, just kill it. This is a very common type of figure of speech in my region. Despite that, various cultures are different and might not have the same phrases commonly used. That's okay, things like this help the world come together to learn about each other. I hope I was able to properly explain it for you so that you don't have to feel bothered about it anymore and you can feel better about continuing to support Gura.

text: I'm not saying this isn't the case, but to add onto it: It's proven that devices know about locations, and who else frequents those locations. If you share space with friends, it will recommend things to them that you're interested in for the sake of getting them to recommend those things to you, and vice versa.
